The most numerous documents, however, are those which have been entered into Chartnlaries, or books, belonging to the monasteries, and preserved by thern as title deeds, charters of privilege and immunity, and either as evidenees of property, or rank, precedence, and authority. The idleness of the cloister was some- times beguiled by copying such chartularies; single sheets might be mislaid or worn out, if too frequently produced for the inspection of either friends or foes; a digested copy of all the land-titles was easier to use, and tended to secure the safety of the originals.
